@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xxiv) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses a `retry` BLOCK (run the body like a `try`; on a failure value
-- re-run, up to `count` attempts). eval runs the body, and on an Error re-executes it (up to
-- the count, or with a backoff schedule); the compute spine has no retry lowering —
-- `normComp`/`norm` reach the `Retry` AST node and refuse it (the `default` arm of `normComp`).
-- The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler
-- frontier, never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment;
-- D1(xv) PAST atom literals; D1(xvi) PAST duration literals; D1(xvii) PAST `for`
-- comprehensions; D1(xviii) PAST integer ranges; D1(xix) PAST index assignment; D1(xx) PAST
-- the `loop` construct; D1(xxi) PAST type tests; D1(xxii) PAST the propagate operator `e?`;
-- D1(xxiii) PAST the prop-with operator `e ?: alt`; D1(xxiv) PAST the `try` block (a
-- Result-collecting `?` scope; see compile_try_test). The frontier now sits at the `retry`
-- block. This file uses one, so it still refuses; when retry lowers (a later D1 slice, a
-- re-run loop around a try body), it flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def flaky(n: Number): Result(Number, String)
  if n > 0 then Ok(n) else Error("neg")

def attempt(n: Number): Result(Number, String)
  retry 3
    flaky(n)

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(attempt(5))
